<article>
    <h1>Light&#xAD;ing up for Ay&#xAD;o&#xAD;d&#xAD;hya event</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200806/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-06"><time>2020-08-06</time></a>
        - <span>BIG PICTURE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Tem­ples and other build­ings on the bank of the Sarayu river seen il­lu­mi­nated on Tues­day, ahead of a foun­da­tion-lay­ing cer­e­mony for a Hindu tem­ple in Ay­o­d­hya, In­dia.</p>
    <p>In­dian Prime Min­is­ter Naren­dra Modi yes­ter­day laid the foun­da­tion stone for the tem­ple on a site where a 16th cen­tury mosque was de­mol­ished by sup­port­ers of his Hindu na­tion­al­ist party in 1992.</p>
    <p>The 1992 in­ci­dent in Ay­o­d­hya sparked com­mu­nal ri­ots in sev­eral parts of In­dia. About 2,000 peo­ple, mostly Mus­lims, were killed.</p>
    <p>The rights to the site were un­re­solved un­til last year, when the Supreme Court de­cided in favour of build­ing a Hindu tem­ple there, on the con­di­tion that Mus­lims were given an­other plot to build a mosque.</p>

